ITU Graphics Programming

Exercise 11 - Ray-traced Cornell box

Learning objectives

This week we will use another different way of rendering objects, using ray-tracing:

  • Learn how to recreate a scene using intersections with rays.
  • Cast rays to get lighting information.
  • Combine rays in different directions to get diverse effects.

Remember that you can find hints in comments in the code, tagged with the label "(todo)" followed by the number of the exercise.

References

  • Cornell box: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornell_box
  • Line-sphere intersection: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line%E2%80%93sphere_intersection
  • IOR list for common materials: http://blendersauce.com/ior-list/

Exercise 11.0 - Quick overview of the code (live)

The teacher will quickly go through the different parts of the code, paying special attention to the ray-tracing algorithm and the objects in the scene.

Exercise 11.1 - Diffuse reflection

If you run the exercise, you will find yourself in a dark room. The camera controller from previous exercises is working, but your only reference is the white area light at the top.

Most of the work in this exercise will be focused in the exercise11.glsl shader file. The initial rays are being cast from the camera and the intersection computed in CastRay(), but the only thing we are doing in ProcessOutput() is returning the emissive light (and that is why we can see the area light.

To turn on the light, we will fake diffuse lighting by casting one single ray directly to the center of the light. It won't reflect the actual area light, but we will change that later. For now:

  1. Find the contact point where the ray is hitting the surface. You can do this starting from the ray position and adding the distance multiplied by the ray direction.
  2. Find the position of the center of the light. We know the coordinates in world space are in (0, CornellBoxSize.y, 0), centered at the top of the box. But we need the position in view space, like everything else. You can use the helper function TransformFromLocal() with the ViewMatrix.
  3. With those 2 positions, we can get the light vector, which will be the direction of the new ray.
  4. Use GetDerivedRay to get a new ray, from the contact position, in the direction to the light.
  5. Because recursive algorithms don't play well with shaders, we queue new rays to be processed sequentially, using PushRay.

Doing this we are casting a new ray, but the color filter of the ray will be the same as the original (starting white). We should multiply the new ray colorFilter variable by these terms:

  • Albedo: The new ray takes the color of the surface we hit.
  • Angle of incidence: As we saw before, the amount of light received depends on the cosine of the angle of incidence, that can be computed as the ClampedDot of the normal and the light direction.
  • Inverse of Pi (InvPi): Because we are using a single ray to account for the light scattered in all directions, we need to normalize dividing by Pi.

Run the program and observe the newly lit room. You will find 2 objects that you may remember from last lecture, a sphere and a box. Use the GUI to modify their parameters, and move around the room using the camera controller, to get familiar with the scene.

Exercise 11.2 - Specular reflection

The next step to simulate the lighting would be the specular reflection. This is one of the features where ray-tracing is better than rasterization, allowing us to get dynamic reflections of the scene.

We will push another ray, this time reflecting the ray like a mirror:

  1. Implement the function GetSpecularReflectionDirection() and use it to compute the reflected direction.
  2. Generate a derived ray from the contact point, using the reflected direction.
  3. Push the new ray.

By doing this, we are splitting each ray in 2, which means that we are adding energy to the scene, unless we do something about it.

We can use the fresnel term, like in exercise08, to divide the energy between diffuse and specular:.

  1. Get the reflectance of the material.
  2. Using the reflectance, the ray direction, and the normal, compute the fresnel term.
  3. Multiply the colorFilter on the new specular ray by the fresnel.
  4. Multiply the colorFilter on the diffuse ray by the inverse of the fresnel.

If you run the program now, you should be able to see some specular highlights from the area light. But we can go even further! If you increase the max ray count in GetRayTracerConfig, you will get more bounces on the reflection. Each bounce duplicates the number of rays needed, so you will need 2 rays for 1 bounce, 6 (2 + 4) for 2 bounces, 14 (2 + 4 + 8) for 3 bounces, etc. However, for performance reasons, the max number is limited to 16 by default, by RayCapacity in raytracer.glsl. You can increase it if your computer can deal with it easily.

Exercise 11.3 - Path tracing

Until this point, we are computing all the rays in a single frame. But this is a problem if we want to simulate more rays, to get proper diffuse lighting, blurry reflections, or soft shadows. To improve that, we will cast rays in random directions and accumulate over the frames.

We will start by casting random rays for the diffuse reflection:

  1. Replace the light direction by the direction obtained with GetDiffuseReflectionDirection. This will give us a different random direction in the hemisphere of the normal.
  2. Remove the InvPi from the diffuse ray colorFilter. Instead, we will account for all the directions doing the average over many frames.
  3. Remove the angle of incidence from the diffuse ray colorFilter. The probability of the directions is computed proportionally to the angle of incidence.

Running with these changes will result in a noisy cloud of points. We need to accumulate over time for it to form a proper image.

If you look carefully at the code in RaymarchingApplication.cpp, you will notice that the raytracing pass is rendering to a separate framebuffer and then copying the results to the default framebuffer. We will use this to store the result of the previous frame in that texture and combine it with current frame using blending:

  1. In InitializeMaterial(), enable blending in the raytracing material by changing the blending equation to "Add".
  2. In the same function, change the material blend params to do "alpha blending": use SourceAlpha and OneMinusSourceAlpha.
  3. In raytracing.frag, compute the alpha value as 1 divided by the total framecount and return it in FragColor.

After the changes, the image will need a few frames to stabilize. If you move the camera or you change any of the uniforms of the scene, the image will be reset.

The resulting image (when it converges) shows much better quality than before. You can see that we get area lights, ambient occlusion and soft shadows "for free" with this technique. Spend some time playing with the parameters of the light and the objects before moving to the next exercise.

Exercise 11.4 - Roughness and metalness

The main problem of the current image is that the reflection is always too sharp, as if the objects were perfectly polished.

If you look at the Material structure declared in exercise11.glsl, you will see that there are 2 fields roughness and metalness that we are not using. The values for them are hardcoded to 0 in all materials. You can expose these values for the sphere and the box, or you can hardcode fixed values directly in the shader.

To use metalness, there is not much to change, as we were already using it in GetReflectance() without knowing it. Just make sure that you use GetAlbedo() instead of material.albedo in the colorFilter for the diffuse ray.

For the roughness, we need to disperse the reflection vector in random directions:

  1. For a better distribution, compute the actual roughness value, as the material.roughness squared.
  2. Mix between the reflected direction and the direction used by the diffuse, using the roughness.
  3. Normalize the result, and use it as the specular ray direction, instead of the reflected direction.

Once again, try with different values of metalness and roughness for the sphere and the box.

Exercise 11.5 - Refraction

The last part of the exercise is probably the most interesting. As we have seen, ray tracing is good for dynamic reflections, ambient occlusion, soft shadows... but it is also good for transparency. Once we have found a hit, we can continue on that same direction, or slighly modified using refraction.

We will implement the refraction reusing the same ray that we have for the diffuse, changing the parameters depending on transparency:

  1. Create a local boolean variable isTransparent. We will consider that it is a transparent material if its IOR is different than the default value of 0.
  2. Create a local boolean variable isExit, to determine if the ray is leaving a transparent material. It will be true when the IOR of the ray is different than 1 (air).
  3. Compute the IOR for the new ray. It will be equal to the material IOR if it is transparent and is not exiting, 1 otherwise.
  4. Implement the function GetRefractedDirection() and use it to obtain the direction of the refracted ray. The third parameter of the function is the ratio between the ray IOR and your new IOR.
  5. When creating the diffuse ray, use the diffuse direction or the refracted direction, depending on the isTransparent variable.
  6. The color filter of the diffuse ray will only be multiplied by the albedo if it is not an exit ray, because we don't want to apply the filter twice.
  7. Finally, assign the computed IOR to the new ray.

To test the refraction, you will need to assign an IOR value to any of the materials. Try different values and observe the different behavior between cubes and spheres. You may need to increase the number of maxRays in the configuration, and possibly the RayCapacity in raytracer.glsl

With this, we finalize all the exercises of the course. I hope you enjoyed them and learn some interesting stuff. Congratulations!

Exercise 11.X - Get creative (optional)

During the exercise we have played with the same scene, but you can easily add new objects to it if you modify the CastRay function.

Try to build a complex scene with inter-reflections and refraction, with boxes and spheres.

Additionally, you can try to get a very cheap form of anti-aliasing. Just add a random offset every frame to the TexCoords before computing the ray origin. The offset has to be a vec2, using Rand01() on each direction, and divided by the window resolution.
